The arguments for and against play-acting here introduced seem to be borrowed from those used in the Rainolds-Gager controversy (on which see an article by Mr F. S. Boas in the Fortnzglctly Review, Aug. 1907). Gager had himself at the end of his play Ulysses Redux (printed 1592) put the arguments against the stage in the mouth of Momus, and then answered them. Rainolds in his Ouertlzrow qutage-playes (1599) deals with these answers. The author of Fucus seems not to have used Gager’s play directly, but to have taken his points on both sides from such passages as the following in Rainolds’ book.

P. 4: the Praetor...saith...1nfamia notatur qui artis ludicrae pronun- tiandive causa in scenam prodierit. And Ulpian...doeth report him so... Ait Praetor, Qui in scenam prodierit infamis est.

P. 8: the lawe of God...forbiddeth a man to put on womans raiment...you answer that it is not vnlawfull simply and alwayes.
